column9:
The name of the currency comes from "pesseta", a Catalan diminutive of the Catalan word peça (meaning piece or fraction) or the Spanish Peso. The word peseta has been known as early as 1737 to colloquially refer to the coin worth 2 reales provincial or ​1⁄5 of a peso.
It was formally introduced as a currency unit in 1868, with 1 peso duro = 5 pesetas. The peseta replaced all previous currencies denominated in silver escudos and reales de vellon at a rate of 5 pesetas = 1 peso duro = 2 silver escudos = 20 reales de vellón.

The name "Euro" was officially adopted on 16 December 1995 in Madrid. The euro was introduced to the financial markets as an accounting currency on 1 January 1999, replacing the former European Currency Unit (ECU) at a ratio of 1:1. Physical euro coins and banknotes entered into circulation on 1 January 2002, as the official currency of the Euro Zone original members, and by March 2002 it had completely replaced the former currencies.
Central bank: European Central Bank
Conversion Rates to the former national currencies.

The silver escudo was one of the currencies of Spain between 1864 and 1869. Some coins and banknotes were produced up to 1873. It was subdivided into 100 céntimos de escudo. The escudo replaced the real de vellon at a rate of 10 reales de vellon = 1 escudo.
The Real de vellón was introduced in 1600 (made of billon, or less than half silver). In 1737 was fixed at ​1⁄20 dollar and equal to 34 maravedíes (hence 1 dollar = 20 reales = 680 maravedíes)
The peseta (peseta guineana) replaced the Spanish peseta at par shortly after gaining independence from Spain the prior year.
